WEBVTT

00:28.188 --> 00:30.856
[ Instrumental plays ]

00:45.705 --> 00:47.973
Girl: This is not a sad story.

00:47.975 --> 00:50.876
Well, that's what you were
thinking, isn't it?

00:54.247 --> 00:56.215
You hear this music,

00:56.217 --> 00:59.418
and you see me pedaling down
some sun-dappled street,

00:59.420 --> 01:02.321
and you think, "uh-oh."

01:02.323 --> 01:04.657
Ow! Oh, my gosh, Maria.

01:04.659 --> 01:06.659
It's a story about my family

01:06.661 --> 01:10.062
and how much we all
love each other.

01:10.064 --> 01:11.730
[ Squeals ] Julie!

01:11.732 --> 01:14.033
Julie's the oldest of
the triplets,

01:14.035 --> 01:17.236
and she never lets the
other two forget it.

01:17.238 --> 01:19.238
[ Laughing, squealing]

01:20.540 --> 01:22.074
I can do this, honey.

01:22.076 --> 01:23.108
Why don't you go...

01:23.110 --> 01:23.943
Narrator: That's Steph.

01:23.945 --> 01:25.845
When she does talk
to my parents,

01:25.847 --> 01:27.513
she usually says the
wrong thing.

01:27.515 --> 01:31.150
And Michael, snark central.

01:31.152 --> 01:32.785
When do we get a break?

01:32.787 --> 01:34.553
Are you in the union?

01:34.555 --> 01:36.522
He's joking, but he means it.

01:36.524 --> 01:38.891
Then there's dad.

01:38.893 --> 01:41.260
Dad doesn't say the wrong thing.

01:41.262 --> 01:42.995
He just doesn't say anything.

01:44.931 --> 01:47.233
This reminds me of
our first date.

01:47.235 --> 01:48.434
Not again.

01:48.436 --> 01:50.135
[ Kids groan ] I want to hear.

01:50.137 --> 01:54.373
He invited me over to a house
he was remodeling

01:54.375 --> 01:55.708
to help peel wallpaper.

01:55.710 --> 01:56.809
Uh-huh. Wow.

01:56.811 --> 01:58.143
You're such a romantic, dad.

01:58.145 --> 02:01.313
I am. On the second date, we
pulled carpeting.

02:01.315 --> 02:02.715
Mm-hmm.

02:02.717 --> 02:03.949
She probably liked it.

02:03.951 --> 02:06.519
Actually, I did, Steph.
We had fun.

02:06.521 --> 02:08.654
Am I right? Yeah.

02:08.656 --> 02:12.424
Steph: Well, that's about all
the fun I can handle.

02:12.426 --> 02:15.628
Nice way to get out of working.

02:15.630 --> 02:18.764
So is that when you fell
in love with mom?

02:18.766 --> 02:21.400
When did you fall in
love with me?

02:21.402 --> 02:23.369
Oh, I-I'll let you know.

02:24.704 --> 02:26.539
[ Both chuckle ]

02:26.541 --> 02:27.873
[ Kiss ]

02:31.378 --> 02:34.914
Hey, you should have called.

02:39.019 --> 02:41.554
"I know mom's unhappy you're
not getting along

02:41.556 --> 02:43.355
"even if she doesn't show it.

02:43.357 --> 02:44.523
You should talk to her."

02:44.525 --> 02:47.026
She thinks it's so easy.

02:52.499 --> 02:53.999
Maria: I guess you could say

02:54.001 --> 02:57.269
my role in the family
is the glue.

02:58.872 --> 03:02.074
I'm always trying to get
everyone to stick together.

03:05.178 --> 03:06.879
I'm not in the mood.

03:06.881 --> 03:09.348
I have a headache.

03:09.350 --> 03:11.483
Want me to fix it?

03:13.653 --> 03:17.256
¶ You could breathe again

03:18.458 --> 03:20.092
¶ you would...

03:22.128 --> 03:23.629
Feel better?

03:23.631 --> 03:25.931
Mm-hmm.

03:25.933 --> 03:29.468
So what will you do when you're
at college and I'm not there?

03:29.470 --> 03:32.237
I'll come see you.

03:32.239 --> 03:33.906
It's not that far.

03:33.908 --> 03:35.240
It's just Boston.

03:35.242 --> 03:39.478
Yeah, but what if you went to
NYU and commuted?

03:39.480 --> 03:41.480
Or if you had a dorm?

03:41.482 --> 03:43.582
I could take the
train on weekends,

03:43.584 --> 03:45.985
and you could pick me up
at grand central.

03:45.987 --> 03:49.888
¶ ...house is falling

03:49.890 --> 03:55.995
¶ your house is falling down

03:57.197 --> 03:59.865
Maria: Even I couldn't
fix everything.

03:59.867 --> 04:01.734
One day at school,

04:01.736 --> 04:04.203
my shoulder started
hurting really bad.

04:04.205 --> 04:08.440
That night, I woke up with the
worst headache in my life.

04:08.442 --> 04:09.875
[ Tires skid ]

04:13.680 --> 04:14.880
Okay.

04:14.882 --> 04:17.048
Here we go. Got her?

04:22.455 --> 04:23.589
Dad.

04:23.591 --> 04:26.392
It's okay, sweetie. I got you.

04:26.394 --> 04:28.060
[ Maria sobs ]

04:35.969 --> 04:37.936
[ Overlapping chatter ] Yeah,
we got him here now.

04:37.938 --> 04:40.572
I want to go home. I know.

04:40.574 --> 04:42.875
I wouldn't worry. If you're
half the S.O.B. Your father is,

04:42.877 --> 04:44.777
we'll have you out of
here by breakfast.

04:44.779 --> 04:47.012
I always treated you like a
lady, didn't I?

04:47.014 --> 04:48.747
Eddie and I did some
business last year.

04:48.749 --> 04:50.716
Oh, he did the business.
I ate crow.

04:50.718 --> 04:52.551
Sorry.

04:52.553 --> 04:54.253
If I didn't have a
taste for crow,

04:54.255 --> 04:56.355
would I be running a
place like this?

04:57.924 --> 05:01.293
Maria: The triplets were
leaving soon for
college in Boston.

05:01.295 --> 05:03.362
I was worried about
being left alone,

05:03.364 --> 05:06.665
but I was more worried
about Michael.

05:06.667 --> 05:08.600
What would he do without me?

05:08.602 --> 05:11.570
¶ On the beach, under the pier

05:11.572 --> 05:14.940
¶ where the cool
kids are so near

05:14.942 --> 05:17.609
¶ it's perfect for a
ladybug's...

05:17.611 --> 05:18.711
Where you going?

05:18.713 --> 05:19.945
Pick up some smokes.

05:19.947 --> 05:21.246
I want to go.

05:21.248 --> 05:22.581
Mom won't let you.

05:22.583 --> 05:25.918
¶ It's perfect for a ladybug

05:27.187 --> 05:28.787
Michael: I can't
believe she caved.

05:28.789 --> 05:32.391
I told her my homework was
done, which it is.

05:32.393 --> 05:35.527
It's just different from how we
grew up. That's all.

05:35.529 --> 05:38.397
You think I'm spoiled?

05:38.399 --> 05:41.800
Well, you are kind of queen of
the universe, right?

05:41.802 --> 05:43.268
[ Both laugh ]

05:44.771 --> 05:46.438
Animal rights activists have...

05:46.440 --> 05:48.307
[ pop ] ¶ I'm gonna let you...
No. Whoa, whoa, whoa.

05:48.309 --> 05:51.577
You can listen to that
corporate crap with
Steph and Julie.

05:51.579 --> 05:52.778
Get a cd.

05:52.780 --> 05:56.348
All my friends listen to
that crap, too.

05:57.484 --> 05:58.817
When you go to Boston,

05:58.819 --> 06:01.754
how am I gonna know what I
should be listening to?

06:01.756 --> 06:03.989
Heh. You never give up, do you?

06:03.991 --> 06:06.358
Yeah, otherwise.

06:06.360 --> 06:07.793
Good choice.

06:07.795 --> 06:10.062
Okay.

06:10.064 --> 06:11.797
[ Rock music plays ]

06:11.799 --> 06:13.766
Seriously, if you go
away to colle...

06:13.768 --> 06:15.934
[ volume increases ]

06:25.645 --> 06:28.514
It's not all my fault.

06:28.516 --> 06:29.648
What?

06:29.650 --> 06:32.518
That I'm supposedly spoiled.

06:32.520 --> 06:35.721
Yeah. Heh. I guess mom just
likes giving you

06:35.723 --> 06:37.356
stuff she couldn't give us.

06:38.725 --> 06:40.793
Before dad made all his money?

06:40.795 --> 06:42.528
I don't mean money.

06:42.530 --> 06:44.396
Like before they got married,

06:44.398 --> 06:48.400
she was just way stressed
trying to handle the three
of us by herself.

06:48.402 --> 06:50.936
I don't think she was ever
really happy till
you came along.

06:50.938 --> 06:53.071
[ Both laugh ]

06:53.073 --> 06:56.742
It's kind of crazy dad married
someone with triplets.

06:56.744 --> 07:00.245
Yeah. Well, he's kind of crazy.

07:00.247 --> 07:04.082
We were very, very cute, though.

07:05.952 --> 07:07.653
Can I have a drag?

07:08.688 --> 07:10.055
Come on. I'm not a baby.

07:10.057 --> 07:13.225
We'll have a smoke together
in a few years.

07:13.227 --> 07:15.561
But by then, I'll have quit.

07:17.831 --> 07:18.931
Julie: I'm really worried.

07:18.933 --> 07:20.966
I know. I know.

07:20.968 --> 07:22.501
Now, the thing about
encephalitis

07:22.503 --> 07:25.671
is that it tends to resolve
itself without any treatment,

07:25.673 --> 07:28.607
so our job is basically seeing
that you stay as comfortable

07:28.609 --> 07:30.075
as possible in the meantime.

07:30.077 --> 07:31.077
How's that sound?

07:31.078 --> 07:32.411
Mom, are you there?

07:32.413 --> 07:34.313
Sorry. We have a G.S.W.
Coming in,

07:34.315 --> 07:36.181
and all the cubicles are taken.

07:36.183 --> 07:37.516
We're almost done. Okay.

07:37.518 --> 07:38.518
Mom?

07:38.519 --> 07:39.885
What's a G.S.W.?

07:39.887 --> 07:41.053
I knew that the pediatrician

07:41.055 --> 07:42.688
was wrong about the backpack,

07:42.690 --> 07:46.758
because a pinched nerve does
not produce
neurological symptoms.

07:46.760 --> 07:48.961
Is a G.S.W. A gunshot wound?

07:48.963 --> 07:50.762
You're too smart for me.

07:50.764 --> 07:52.931
Oh, my God. This place...

07:52.933 --> 07:53.899
[ Doors bang open ] Excuse me!

07:53.901 --> 07:55.133
Doctor: Tell me about it,

07:55.135 --> 07:56.301
but you're safe here.
[ Baby cries ]

07:56.303 --> 07:57.669
Man: You gotta stay
with your family.

07:57.671 --> 08:00.439
I'll get you some water and
settle your nerves.

08:00.441 --> 08:02.174
Julie: What do they
think happened?

08:02.176 --> 08:04.676
Well, she probably got it
from the tick.

08:04.678 --> 08:05.978
Keep you hydrated.

08:05.980 --> 08:07.346
[ P.A. ] Nurse Carson,

08:07.348 --> 08:08.914
you have a phone call, line one.

08:08.916 --> 08:10.883
Nurse Carson, you have a
phone call, line one.

08:10.885 --> 08:12.050
All right, Julie, listen.

08:12.052 --> 08:13.485
She's gonna be fine.

08:13.487 --> 08:15.020
Should we take the train
down tomorrow?

08:15.022 --> 08:16.221
Julie, just... no. Stay...

08:16.223 --> 08:17.923
stay put. Finish your
week's classes.

08:17.925 --> 08:19.524
Okay, mom. Just let me know.

08:19.526 --> 08:20.526
Okay.

08:20.527 --> 08:22.427
[ Overlapping chatter ]

08:24.964 --> 08:26.398
Are we ever gonna find this
young lady a bed?

08:26.400 --> 08:29.034
Sorry. As you've
undoubtedly noticed,

08:29.036 --> 08:31.036
we've got serious
space issues here.

08:31.038 --> 08:32.104
This is Mr. Marchwinski.

08:32.106 --> 08:33.538
He's our P.R. Guy.

08:33.539 --> 08:36.008
That's why he's
advertising our problems.

08:36.010 --> 08:37.542
No wonder we're going broke.

08:37.544 --> 08:38.710
I got to go.

08:38.712 --> 08:40.679
Can I just get over there?

08:40.681 --> 08:41.914
Eddie's... Eddie's amazing.

08:41.916 --> 08:43.381
We may be a lowly
county hospital,

08:43.384 --> 08:45.484
but he gets us the best
doctors in the world.

08:45.486 --> 08:46.985
We heard. That's why we
drove to Westchester

08:46.987 --> 08:48.053
instead of our local hospital.

08:48.055 --> 08:49.888
I'm glad you did. So, Maria,

08:49.890 --> 08:51.556
is there anything I
can do for you?

08:52.592 --> 08:53.792
Paint the walls something

08:53.794 --> 08:55.627
that doesn't make me
hate my life.

08:55.629 --> 08:57.062
Maria, this is a hospital.

08:57.064 --> 08:59.097
No, she's right. I mean,
what does

08:59.099 --> 09:01.400
a place that looks like
this communicate?

09:01.402 --> 09:03.535
That's how my dad
talks to people,

09:03.537 --> 09:05.237
by building things.

09:05.239 --> 09:07.472
Well, that must make for
slow conversations.

09:07.474 --> 09:09.107
[ Chuckles ]

09:09.109 --> 09:11.677
Maria: How do you know if
a boy likes you?

09:11.679 --> 09:15.080
Judging from mom and dad, I
wouldn't have a clue.

09:15.082 --> 09:18.083
Yeah, they work together,

09:18.085 --> 09:20.686
but what about the
rest of the time?

09:20.688 --> 09:23.488
Look, I want to float the walls
of the storage space,

09:23.490 --> 09:25.791
or it'll look like a
fortress in here.

09:25.793 --> 09:28.493
We're gonna move that
load-bearing wall two
feet the other way.

09:28.495 --> 09:29.995
That's going to be
repermitting there,

09:29.997 --> 09:31.997
and that could hold us up
for a few weeks.

09:31.999 --> 09:33.865
Just do it, and I'll talk

09:33.867 --> 09:35.534
to the building
department later.

09:35.536 --> 09:37.135
You're the boss.

09:40.340 --> 09:41.373
What?

09:41.375 --> 09:43.008
Nothing.

09:43.010 --> 09:44.242
Nothing?

09:44.244 --> 09:45.711
Put your helmet on, tough guy.

09:45.713 --> 09:48.647
Listen, it's easier to ask
for forgiveness...

09:48.649 --> 09:50.515
than permission. Okay, dad.

09:50.517 --> 09:54.086
Hey, did you go to school with
a guy named Kerrigan?

09:54.088 --> 09:55.754
Kerrigan? Yeah.

09:55.756 --> 09:57.322
I don't know. Maybe. Why?

09:57.324 --> 09:58.657
His son's in my class.

09:58.659 --> 10:01.126
Maybe you should invite the
Kerrigans for dinner.

10:01.128 --> 10:03.362
Ah, maybe I should invite
the other 800 guys

10:03.364 --> 10:04.997
I went to school with, too.

10:04.999 --> 10:06.231
Maybe you should.

10:06.233 --> 10:08.266
Can we stop at Ben & Jerry's?

10:08.268 --> 10:10.235
Who is this Ben and Jerry?

10:10.237 --> 10:11.636
I don't know these boys.

10:11.638 --> 10:12.471
Lame.

10:12.473 --> 10:14.072
No, we gotta pick up your mom.

10:14.074 --> 10:15.540
She's been doing
interiors all day.

10:15.542 --> 10:17.142
Work, work, work.

10:17.144 --> 10:20.545
Maria: I don't think I'd want
to work with my husband,

10:20.547 --> 10:22.881
unless his job was
making ice cream.

10:22.883 --> 10:24.549
Then I guess I could handle it.

10:24.551 --> 10:26.218
I don't think your dad likes me.

10:26.220 --> 10:28.887
What are you talking about?

10:28.889 --> 10:31.189
Like, he never talks to me.

10:31.191 --> 10:33.458
Yeah, well, that's
just how he is.

10:33.460 --> 10:35.227
He doesn't really
talk to anyone.

10:35.229 --> 10:37.229
Your mom's easy to talk to.

10:37.231 --> 10:38.997
Yeah, but she talks too much.

10:38.999 --> 10:39.999
[ Girls laugh ]

10:40.000 --> 10:41.099
I want that rock.

10:41.101 --> 10:42.367
No, I want that one.

10:42.369 --> 10:43.802
Well, that's really fair, guys.

10:46.739 --> 10:51.276
¶ You say that I'm
messing with your head

10:51.278 --> 10:53.278
¶ yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah

10:53.280 --> 10:54.813
Avril's corporate crap.

10:54.815 --> 10:56.948
No, she's not.

10:56.950 --> 10:58.784
Oh, know what?

10:58.786 --> 10:59.786
What?

10:59.787 --> 11:00.787
Max Kerrigan

11:00.788 --> 11:02.521
was behind me on the bus,

11:02.523 --> 11:04.189
and he kind of pulled my hair,

11:04.191 --> 11:06.958
and he was like, "you
have a lot of hair."

11:06.960 --> 11:09.227
Well, you do. Yeah.

11:09.229 --> 11:11.997
Then he was like, "you don't
know where I live,

11:11.999 --> 11:13.832
"'cause I get off the bus first,

11:13.834 --> 11:15.133
"but I know where you live,

11:15.135 --> 11:16.468
'cause our dads went to
school together."

11:16.470 --> 11:18.804
That's totally illogical.

11:18.806 --> 11:21.573
Maybe he likes you.

11:21.575 --> 11:23.275
[ Laughing ]

11:23.277 --> 11:25.844
¶ And now I figure
what the hell?

11:25.846 --> 11:29.614
Oh, my God. Really? ¶ all I
want is to mess around

11:29.616 --> 11:32.951
¶ and I don't really care about

11:32.953 --> 11:36.488
¶ if you love me, if you hate me

11:36.490 --> 11:39.591
¶ you can save me, baby, baby

11:39.593 --> 11:42.427
¶ all my life I've been good,
but now

11:42.429 --> 11:45.897
¶ whoa, I'm thinking
what the hell

11:45.899 --> 11:47.699
¶ what the hell

11:47.701 --> 11:50.769
¶ LA-LA-LA-LA-LA-LA

11:50.771 --> 11:52.971
¶ whoa

11:55.041 --> 11:56.208
Maria: I'm gonna fall.

11:56.210 --> 11:59.211
I need to lie down.

11:59.213 --> 12:00.779
You are. You're in bed.

12:03.816 --> 12:05.951
What kind of house is this?

12:05.953 --> 12:07.352
It's a hospital.

12:08.688 --> 12:11.490
Oh, right.

12:11.492 --> 12:14.593
It sucks here, but you'll
get used to it.

12:14.595 --> 12:17.829
I've been coming here since I
was, like, three.

12:19.832 --> 12:21.399
My arm just jumped.

12:25.238 --> 12:28.106
[ Chuckles ] That
was a good one.

12:28.108 --> 12:30.942
Go, go, go, go.

12:30.944 --> 12:32.110
I got something!

12:32.112 --> 12:33.478
Fight it! Fight it! Oh, my God.

12:33.480 --> 12:35.113
Just reel, reel, reel, reel!

12:35.115 --> 12:36.115
[ Laughs ]

12:36.116 --> 12:37.449
What do I do?

12:37.451 --> 12:39.117
Give it some muscle.

12:39.119 --> 12:41.520
Oh, my God. Here it comes. Oh,
I can see it.

12:41.522 --> 12:42.888
I can see it. It's huge.

12:42.890 --> 12:44.256
What? It's huge.

12:44.258 --> 12:45.957
I don't want to look. I'm
reeling it in.

12:45.959 --> 12:47.325
No slack. Here. Hey, here...

12:47.327 --> 12:49.861
oh, yes, look at the size of it.

12:49.863 --> 12:51.263
That is a record.

12:51.265 --> 12:52.564
That is twice the size

12:52.566 --> 12:54.666
of the garbage bag I
caught last week.

12:54.668 --> 12:56.601
It's not funny! You know what?

12:56.603 --> 12:58.503
Should we bring it home
for mom to clean,

12:58.505 --> 12:59.771
and we'll eat it later?

12:59.773 --> 13:01.907
You want to stuff it and
mount it on your wall?

13:01.909 --> 13:03.041
It's a beauty.

13:03.043 --> 13:05.343
Maria: See? My dad's
not all bad.

13:05.345 --> 13:07.746
He's not even part bad, really.

13:16.455 --> 13:20.559
The thing that changes your
life forever can be big,

13:20.561 --> 13:22.427
like falling in love.

13:24.931 --> 13:26.765
Or small,

13:26.767 --> 13:30.001
so small that it doesn't
even leave a mark.

13:30.003 --> 13:32.437
[ Squeaks ]

13:36.876 --> 13:38.143
[ Door closes ]

13:38.145 --> 13:40.345
[ P.A. ] Dr. Snow,
please call...

13:40.347 --> 13:42.614
You know, when they let her
out in the morning,

13:42.616 --> 13:44.182
she and I can take a cab.

13:44.184 --> 13:46.084
You should go home and
get some sleep.

13:46.086 --> 13:47.752
What about you? You... you go.

13:47.754 --> 13:51.356
No. I'm not the one that has a
meeting with Turner at 9:30.

13:51.358 --> 13:53.725
Yeah, yeah. Come here.

14:06.272 --> 14:11.243
Hey, I really liked
yesterday's entry.

14:11.245 --> 14:13.211
You didn't!

14:13.213 --> 14:15.847
[ Laughs ]

14:15.849 --> 14:18.550
If you ever...

14:18.552 --> 14:19.818
Dad says it's easier

14:19.820 --> 14:22.687
to ask for forgiveness
than permission.

14:22.689 --> 14:25.924
I guess that's why he
does what he wants,

14:25.926 --> 14:28.593
then asks questions later.

14:28.595 --> 14:32.230
It's also why some people
don't like him.

14:32.232 --> 14:34.933
Woman: Mr. Fareri
proposes building

14:34.935 --> 14:37.602
17 luxury residences

14:37.604 --> 14:41.606
on the 140 acres of the
former Gimbel estate.

14:41.608 --> 14:46.478
Time and again, he's maneuvered
around zoning restrictions

14:46.480 --> 14:48.580
and the will of this council,

14:48.582 --> 14:53.251
contributing to the unchecked
growth of our community.

14:53.253 --> 14:55.520
We used to live like neighbors,

14:55.522 --> 14:57.455
talk to one another.

14:57.457 --> 15:02.861
Now we hide out behind the
walls of luxury homes.

15:02.863 --> 15:08.033
But who wants to talk to their
neighbors, anyway?

15:08.035 --> 15:09.934
Thank you.

15:33.926 --> 15:36.795
Woman: Come on. You
want to find...

15:36.797 --> 15:38.363
[ Boy chatters ]

15:38.365 --> 15:41.366
I'm sorry. Can we, uh,
have a moment here?

15:41.368 --> 15:43.268
Sure. Uh, hey,

15:43.270 --> 15:46.705
come on. Come on.

15:46.707 --> 15:47.639
Come on.

15:47.641 --> 15:49.174
Boy: Why do we have to go?

15:49.176 --> 15:50.909
Hope you're feeling better,
Austin.

15:50.911 --> 15:55.714
Uh, we just wanted to ask if
there's any chance

15:55.716 --> 15:57.682
that either of you were aware of

15:57.684 --> 16:00.785
that Maria might have been
bitten by an animal

16:00.787 --> 16:04.489
in the past few months?
Scratched?

16:04.491 --> 16:07.525
Other than the tick?

16:07.527 --> 16:10.161
I mean, not that I'm aware of,
but...

16:10.163 --> 16:12.997
As you know, she's grown worse.

16:12.999 --> 16:15.700
I think we actually have to
consider another
possibility here.

16:15.702 --> 16:17.635
What?

16:17.637 --> 16:21.406
That, uh, Maria may have
contracted rabies.

16:21.408 --> 16:23.074
[ Gasps ]

16:23.076 --> 16:25.577
They tell me that the odds of
it being rabies are tiny,

16:25.579 --> 16:26.945
like 160 million to one.

16:26.947 --> 16:29.347
They're gonna run some tests,
but odds are,

16:29.349 --> 16:30.749
it's encephalitis,
overwhelmingly.

16:30.751 --> 16:32.851
What if it were rabies?

16:32.853 --> 16:33.685
What will we do?

16:33.687 --> 16:36.087
Noth... there's nothing.

16:37.189 --> 16:38.623
Well, we've already gone ahead

16:38.625 --> 16:40.692
and contacted the center
for disease control

16:40.694 --> 16:42.026
and the pasteur institute

16:42.028 --> 16:43.762
looking for any insights

16:43.764 --> 16:46.231
they can provide us with
moving forward,

16:46.233 --> 16:48.800
but main thing we
want to do now,

16:48.802 --> 16:50.935
we want to try and slow
her system down

16:50.937 --> 16:53.605
so that she has the energy
to fight the virus,

16:53.607 --> 16:55.573
which would also help with
the encephalitis,

16:55.575 --> 16:57.842
if that's what it
turns out to be.

16:57.844 --> 17:02.113
Do it. Whatever it takes,
do it.

17:17.329 --> 17:19.731
[ Cries ]

17:19.733 --> 17:21.933
[ Respirator pumping ]

18:16.288 --> 18:17.288
Excuse me. Yes?

18:17.290 --> 18:18.890
Are you Mrs. Fareri? Yeah.

18:18.892 --> 18:20.758
I wonder if you had a
moment for me.

18:20.760 --> 18:22.327
I just had a couple
of questions.

18:27.633 --> 18:29.868
[ Overlapping chatter ]

18:32.805 --> 18:34.405
She does not have rabies,

18:34.407 --> 18:35.874
and this is not a news story.

18:35.876 --> 18:37.609
This is my daughter that
we're speaking about.

18:37.611 --> 18:38.943
I understand, but if
there's a chance

18:38.945 --> 18:40.778
there's rabies in the area,
people should...

18:40.780 --> 18:42.714
miss, miss, the emergency
room is that way.

18:42.716 --> 18:44.015
I'm not looking for the
emergency room.

18:44.017 --> 18:46.484
You will be in about
two seconds.

18:46.486 --> 18:48.286
You understand?

18:53.492 --> 18:55.026
I don't know how they
got your name.

18:55.028 --> 18:56.227
We've tried to keep this quiet.

18:56.229 --> 18:59.364
Well, this woman had no
trouble finding me.

18:59.366 --> 19:02.400
If I find out who leaked it...

19:02.402 --> 19:04.369
clearly we need to run
a tighter ship

19:04.371 --> 19:06.237
around here in more
ways than one.

19:06.239 --> 19:08.139
Let... let me go see

19:08.141 --> 19:10.475
if there's anything I can
do for you guys.

19:10.477 --> 19:13.111
[ Wheel thumping ]

19:13.113 --> 19:14.913
Hyah.

19:35.601 --> 19:37.969
[ Indistinct P.A.
Announcement ]

19:44.243 --> 19:46.244
[ Mop slapping ]

19:50.349 --> 19:52.016
Mom.

19:53.018 --> 19:54.452
Mom.

19:55.654 --> 19:56.788
Mom.

19:56.790 --> 19:57.989
I'm here, Maria.

19:57.991 --> 19:59.857
It's us.

20:01.827 --> 20:04.228
You guys look awful.

20:11.070 --> 20:13.104
Come here.

20:15.608 --> 20:17.809
[ Respirator pumping ]

20:25.417 --> 20:27.986
Why did she tell us not to come?

20:58.417 --> 21:00.585
[ Crying ]

21:05.090 --> 21:06.924
Why won't you at least try it?

21:06.926 --> 21:09.594
Well, number one, it's too
sparkly for me,

21:09.596 --> 21:13.431
and, number two, that's
not my color.

21:13.433 --> 21:14.999
Don't you just die of boredom

21:15.001 --> 21:16.834
putting on the same thing
day after day,

21:16.836 --> 21:20.505
month after month,
year after year?

21:20.507 --> 21:22.273
Nope.

21:22.275 --> 21:24.275
[ Crying ]

21:32.985 --> 21:35.953
Mom, you're missing a diamond.

21:35.955 --> 21:38.523
I know. I know. I'm looking for
it. Don't tell dad.

21:38.525 --> 21:40.324
What, he hasn't noticed?

21:40.326 --> 21:41.759
Heh. Your father?

21:41.761 --> 21:43.861
Hey, will you leave
your mom alone?

21:43.863 --> 21:44.996
She takes long enough without

21:44.998 --> 21:46.531
you distracting her.
We gotta go.

21:46.533 --> 21:47.965
I-I'm ready.

21:50.302 --> 21:51.903
Shh. Don't tell.

21:51.905 --> 21:53.104
Pinky swear.

22:04.817 --> 22:07.185
Listen, you gotta get
over this thing.

22:08.253 --> 22:11.055
I, uh...

22:11.057 --> 22:15.393
I got us tickets to see an
otherwise concert.

22:16.695 --> 22:18.863
And rob really wants to come
with me, but I...

22:18.865 --> 22:23.000
I'd be pretty pissed if I have
to go with that clown.

22:23.002 --> 22:25.870
I know you got a crush on him,

22:25.872 --> 22:30.041
but I got that ticket for you,
so...

22:32.244 --> 22:35.179
You do what you gotta do, okay?

22:52.798 --> 22:53.798
Hey, what's up?

22:53.800 --> 22:55.600
Nothing much.

23:07.112 --> 23:08.112
Oh, wow.

23:09.148 --> 23:10.214
What?

23:11.283 --> 23:12.283
Nothing.

23:13.986 --> 23:16.687
I think your mom's been
looking for that.

23:22.494 --> 23:24.862
Maria: Boys are so immature.

23:24.864 --> 23:28.599
Oliver called Amy a
freakazoid today.

23:28.601 --> 23:31.803
Real subtle, Oliver.

23:31.805 --> 23:33.738
[ Winces ]

23:33.740 --> 23:36.007
I mean...

23:39.711 --> 23:41.746
It's so obvious he likes her.

23:41.748 --> 23:44.515
Why doesn't he just tell her?

23:44.517 --> 23:49.654
Wouldn't it be easier if people
just said exactly what
they were thinking?

23:52.024 --> 23:54.425
But I guess then I'd have
to do it, too.

23:55.794 --> 23:58.229
Maybe it's not that easy.

23:59.097 --> 24:01.265
[ Respirator pumping ]

24:12.077 --> 24:14.612
You looking for something?

24:14.614 --> 24:16.614
My long-lost innocence.

24:16.616 --> 24:18.149
Ask your mother.

24:24.523 --> 24:26.224
Maria?

24:27.259 --> 24:30.628
Hi there. Did you finish
your homework?

24:30.630 --> 24:32.697
Yeah.

24:32.699 --> 24:36.133
Why doesn't daddy talk more?

24:36.135 --> 24:38.769
Did you just try to talk to him?

24:38.771 --> 24:40.438
Yeah.

24:42.641 --> 24:44.775
It's just... it's
just who he is.

24:44.777 --> 24:47.245
It doesn't mean that
he's angry at you.

24:47.247 --> 24:49.881
Duh. Why would you
even say that?

24:49.883 --> 24:51.883
Because when we were
first married,

24:51.885 --> 24:53.784
he wouldn't talk to me
all that much,

24:53.786 --> 24:55.853
and it kind of scared me.

24:55.855 --> 24:57.421
Why?

25:06.965 --> 25:09.467
I know...

25:09.469 --> 25:11.602
Sometimes...

25:13.438 --> 25:14.705
I'm...

25:20.512 --> 25:23.014
Maria: I'm gonna tell daddy to
talk to you more.

25:23.016 --> 25:25.082
No. No, no, no, honey. No,
don't.

25:25.084 --> 25:27.718
Thank you anyway, but don't...
don't mention it, okay?

25:27.720 --> 25:29.854
Daddy has a lot on his mind.

25:29.856 --> 25:30.856
Okay.

25:30.857 --> 25:32.189
What's okay?

25:33.292 --> 25:34.458
Nothing.

25:40.866 --> 25:42.833
You're a good girl.

25:46.071 --> 25:47.838
You're the best girl.

26:07.292 --> 26:09.660
We got the diagnosis.

26:12.564 --> 26:16.033
The DNA is consistent with a
strain of rabies

26:16.035 --> 26:19.537
found in silver-haired bats.

26:19.539 --> 26:24.208
The bite itself would
barely leave a mark.

26:24.210 --> 26:27.211
It might well have occurred
while she was sleeping,

26:27.213 --> 26:30.281
which would explain why
you wouldn't know.

26:30.283 --> 26:32.850
But I don't understand,
because you said

26:32.852 --> 26:38.189
the chances were 160
million to one.

26:38.191 --> 26:40.124
That statistic is accurate.

26:40.126 --> 26:42.093
I'm sorry.

26:42.095 --> 26:43.661
I'm so sorry.

26:44.730 --> 26:46.030
So?

26:46.032 --> 26:48.199
You see, once there's
symptoms of rabies,

26:48.201 --> 26:50.301
there's nothing more
anyone can do.

26:50.303 --> 26:53.004
Now, her eyes are no longer
reacting to light.

26:53.006 --> 26:55.439
We've given her two EEGs,

26:55.441 --> 26:57.341
which are the... the
brainwaves test,

26:57.343 --> 27:01.045
standard protocol before
removing life support.

27:01.047 --> 27:03.514
Removing life support?

27:05.017 --> 27:06.717
Yeah.

27:12.457 --> 27:15.993
Do you, um, have a room where
I can go and cry?

27:15.995 --> 27:18.229
We don't really have
any private...

27:18.231 --> 27:20.664
why don't I find you an office?

27:25.504 --> 27:27.805
Michael: We should go see her.

27:32.677 --> 27:34.678
[ Crying ]

27:36.148 --> 27:38.349
[ Respirator pumping ]

28:00.072 --> 28:02.339
Maria: I knew you were there.

28:02.341 --> 28:04.542
I knew you were all there.

28:10.882 --> 28:12.683
Doctor: We're ready.

28:12.685 --> 28:15.886
So who would like to
be in the room?

28:32.370 --> 28:35.773
Last summer, mom smelled
smoke in the house.

28:35.775 --> 28:37.508
Of course she blamed me.

28:38.944 --> 28:40.678
She was giving me the
third degree,

28:40.680 --> 28:43.547
so finally told her that
Maria had snuck one.

28:43.549 --> 28:45.216
Maria must have killed you.

28:45.218 --> 28:46.951
[ Laughs ] Yeah, she wanted to.

28:48.186 --> 28:50.254
But I let her tweeze
my eyebrows.

28:50.256 --> 28:52.556
It was like her dream come true.

28:59.197 --> 29:01.365
I'm not gonna go back to school.

29:01.367 --> 29:02.600
I can't handle it.

29:02.602 --> 29:05.369
I'm going to stay here
for mom and dad.

29:26.324 --> 29:28.526
[ Respirator pumping ]

29:30.428 --> 29:33.631
Nurse: I'm sorry. You
can't be on the bed.

29:33.633 --> 29:34.932
What?

29:34.934 --> 29:36.567
It's against regulations.

29:36.569 --> 29:38.569
What are you talking about?

29:38.571 --> 29:41.038
No, no, I-it's fine. Stay put.

29:41.040 --> 29:43.107
I'll take responsibility.

30:27.185 --> 30:29.386
[ Alarm sounding ]

30:38.029 --> 30:39.029
[ Alarm fades ]

31:05.023 --> 31:06.991
It's mommy, Maria.

31:06.993 --> 31:08.459
I'm with you.

31:13.398 --> 31:15.165
I'm with you.

31:43.428 --> 31:44.695
[ Overlapping chatter ]

31:44.697 --> 31:47.064
outside the home of John
and Brenda Fareri,

31:47.066 --> 31:48.632
whose daughter Maria has died

31:48.634 --> 31:50.634
after contracting rabies,

31:50.636 --> 31:52.970
her death caused by a
silver-haired bat.

31:52.972 --> 31:56.840
She passed away after just 10
short days in the hospital.

31:56.842 --> 31:59.910
Deaths from rabies are an
extremely rare occurrence.

31:59.912 --> 32:02.613
[ Telephone rings ]

32:03.848 --> 32:06.283
They'll lose
interest eventually.

32:06.285 --> 32:07.851
[ Ring ]

32:10.221 --> 32:13.957
[ Ring ]

32:15.694 --> 32:17.761
[ Ring ]

32:23.868 --> 32:25.903
Bye. Bye.

32:30.275 --> 32:31.809
You guys don't have to wait.

32:31.811 --> 32:33.043
No, it's fine.

32:35.413 --> 32:37.614
Let's just get this over with.

32:39.117 --> 32:40.184
Okay.

32:45.423 --> 32:47.124
Love you.

32:47.126 --> 32:48.525
Come here.

32:49.327 --> 32:51.028
Take care, okay?

32:51.030 --> 32:52.329
Yeah.

32:52.331 --> 32:53.331
See you soon.

32:53.332 --> 32:54.531
Okay.

33:00.505 --> 33:02.506
I'm going to get a job.

33:02.508 --> 33:03.774
I'm gonna look tomorrow.

33:03.776 --> 33:06.210
I didn't say anything, honey.

33:06.212 --> 33:07.511
[ Train horn honks ]

33:07.513 --> 33:09.012
[ P.A. ] Can I have your
attention, please.

33:09.014 --> 33:10.014
All service to...

33:24.963 --> 33:27.197
[ Rock music playing
over headphones ]

33:37.275 --> 33:38.275
Hey.

33:39.778 --> 33:42.279
Did you go to any classes today?

33:43.982 --> 33:45.182
[ Sighs ]

33:52.557 --> 33:54.758
[ Children yelling, talking ]

34:35.766 --> 34:37.967
[ Vacuum whirring ]

34:54.152 --> 34:56.152
[ Tools whirring ]

34:58.490 --> 35:00.691
[ No audible dialogue ]

35:29.921 --> 35:31.655
Brenda: Just tell the
bursar's office

35:31.657 --> 35:33.156
to send us whatever it is

35:33.158 --> 35:35.292
they're worried about, and
I'll... I'll fix it.

35:35.294 --> 35:36.393
Okay, I will.

35:36.395 --> 35:38.262
Your sister got a job
as a barista.

35:38.264 --> 35:39.663
Cool.

35:39.665 --> 35:41.632
And, um...

35:41.634 --> 35:45.202
We ought to start thinking
about Christmas.

35:45.204 --> 35:47.471
Yeah.

35:47.473 --> 35:50.007
Maybe we could just be together,

35:50.009 --> 35:51.275
but...

35:52.911 --> 35:56.713
Like maybe if we went somewhere
that's not Christmassy.

35:56.715 --> 35:58.949
[ "Joy to the world"
instrumental playing ]

36:02.086 --> 36:03.387
Merry Christmas.

36:10.061 --> 36:13.096
Oh, you expect someone
else to join?

36:14.599 --> 36:16.833
No.

36:22.473 --> 36:23.907
Happy Christmas.

36:32.850 --> 36:35.686
Michael: I feel like there was
more food here earlier.

36:35.688 --> 36:36.920
Brenda: We ate it.

36:36.922 --> 36:38.822
No, but there was, like,
plates and stuff.

36:38.824 --> 36:40.324
There was more.

36:40.326 --> 36:41.525
More... there was more here.

36:41.527 --> 36:43.660
Yes, there was a piece of fish.

36:43.662 --> 36:44.728
It's, like, all here.

36:44.730 --> 36:46.296
Very rich. It's very rich.

36:47.665 --> 36:50.000
I'm solid for as in
science and math.

36:50.002 --> 36:51.568
It's history that worries me,

36:51.570 --> 36:53.937
so I'm gonna ask for some
extra-credit work.

36:53.939 --> 36:56.373
Maybe you should talk to your
guidance counselor.

36:56.375 --> 36:58.508
It's not that bad, like an a-,

36:58.510 --> 37:01.044
but I know I can get it to an a.

37:01.046 --> 37:02.346
That's what I mean, sweetie.

37:02.348 --> 37:04.381
You know, you hear about kids

37:04.383 --> 37:05.916
committing suicide
in high school

37:05.918 --> 37:07.818
because they get their first B.

37:07.820 --> 37:10.621
Maybe it would be better to
get it over with

37:10.623 --> 37:11.888
and just get one now.

37:11.890 --> 37:14.858
Oh, my God. You are so mental.

37:14.860 --> 37:16.927
Come on, dad. Come on, dad.

37:16.929 --> 37:20.230
Uh, sorry. I push where?

37:20.232 --> 37:21.131
Where?

37:21.133 --> 37:23.500
That one right on the top,
right...

37:23.502 --> 37:26.003
shit.

37:30.608 --> 37:34.778
We need to decide on the
paneling today.

37:34.780 --> 37:37.681
Here's the breakdown if we go
with the quarter oak.

37:37.683 --> 37:40.150
And if we go with...

37:47.025 --> 37:48.992
John.

38:46.718 --> 38:48.218
John: "This may sound mean,

38:48.220 --> 38:52.122
but I have to admit I hope Amy
isn't as popular as..."

38:52.124 --> 38:54.324
Maria: As she was
in sixth grade.

38:54.326 --> 38:57.194
It's kind of hard to have one
of your best friends

38:57.196 --> 38:59.396
incredibly popular
with everyone.

38:59.398 --> 39:00.764
[ Chuckles ]

39:00.766 --> 39:03.467
Oh, we had to write our top wish

39:03.469 --> 39:05.068
in English class today,

39:05.070 --> 39:08.171
and even though I have a
million wishes for me,

39:08.173 --> 39:11.408
like being a star or a really
famous scientist,

39:11.410 --> 39:13.877
I wished for the health
and well-being

39:13.879 --> 39:16.580
of all the children
in the world.

39:16.582 --> 39:17.981
It's weird.

39:17.983 --> 39:21.485
John: "It's like it just
wrote itself."

39:45.977 --> 39:47.210
Are you ready, John?

39:47.212 --> 39:49.713
Tamar wants us to
stop by the site

39:49.715 --> 39:51.748
before we go to the office.

39:51.750 --> 39:53.016
[ Door closes ]

39:54.485 --> 39:56.486
John.

39:56.488 --> 39:58.588
John?

40:02.126 --> 40:03.627
John?

40:26.551 --> 40:28.118
Why aren't you at work?

40:28.120 --> 40:31.421
Dad got pulled in to some
meetings, and...

40:32.723 --> 40:34.224
Are you all right?

40:34.226 --> 40:35.091
Yeah.

40:35.093 --> 40:37.561
Are you sure? Can I
do anything?

40:37.563 --> 40:38.995
No. Thank you.

40:38.997 --> 40:41.264
I don't... I don't think anyone
can get this out.

40:41.266 --> 40:43.600
It's gotten into the
metal or something.

40:45.570 --> 40:47.237
Okay.

41:10.995 --> 41:12.629
[ Sighs ]

41:37.722 --> 41:39.789
[ Door opens ]

41:39.791 --> 41:41.625
[ Door closes ]

41:41.627 --> 41:43.093
[ Sighs ]

41:55.172 --> 41:59.042
Your dinner's on the stove
if you're hungry.

41:59.044 --> 42:00.844
Thanks.

42:06.951 --> 42:11.621
¶ Trouble's waiting
on the corner

42:14.659 --> 42:19.296
¶ he's been telling you
that I'll be there

42:22.066 --> 42:24.634
¶ I'm losing [ Sighs ]

42:24.636 --> 42:28.104
¶ I'm losing you now

42:28.106 --> 42:29.539
[ arguing ]

42:29.541 --> 42:31.942
Brenda: Were you just going to
run out of the house?

42:31.944 --> 42:33.043
Were you gonna leave a note?

42:33.045 --> 42:34.311
Yes. I did leave a note.

42:34.313 --> 42:35.779
So I'm supposed to
approve of you

42:35.781 --> 42:37.047
going off to Seattle
with some boy

42:37.049 --> 42:38.515
that we haven't even met?

42:38.517 --> 42:40.650
What is in Seattle?
What's here?

42:40.652 --> 42:42.385
I have a job at a coffee shop

42:42.387 --> 42:43.920
where I'm a sitting
duck for people

42:43.922 --> 42:45.322
to continually come in and say,

42:45.324 --> 42:46.489
"be strong for your parents."

42:46.491 --> 42:48.491
Right, like I didn't
lose anything.

42:48.493 --> 42:52.662
I can't believe you're using
Maria to rationalize this.

42:52.664 --> 42:55.065
Don't you understand anything?

42:55.067 --> 42:58.201
What is it that I
don't understand?

42:58.203 --> 43:00.804
Dad is this zombie,

43:00.806 --> 43:02.305
and you go around cleaning,

43:02.307 --> 43:04.507
pretending that
everything's fine.

43:04.509 --> 43:07.243
Maria was the only one
who could get away

43:07.245 --> 43:09.813
with talking about anything
that mattered around here...

43:12.149 --> 43:13.717
So I'm leaving.

43:29.700 --> 43:33.136
Maria: Picking my top wish
seemed hard at first.

43:33.138 --> 43:35.705
I mean, I have a lot of 'em,

43:35.707 --> 43:39.876
like I want to make a
difference in the world.

43:39.878 --> 43:42.078
I know. It sounds cheesy,

43:42.080 --> 43:45.048
but I want to help people.

43:45.050 --> 43:46.950
[ Vacuum whirring ]

43:46.952 --> 43:48.985
Dad builds these huge buildings,

43:48.987 --> 43:51.254
and mom makes them look great,

43:51.256 --> 43:54.958
and that makes people happy.

43:54.960 --> 43:57.293
And someday I want to figure out

43:57.295 --> 43:59.362
my own way to make people happy.

44:00.798 --> 44:02.232
[ Laughs ]

44:02.234 --> 44:04.667
But that isn't the wish I
picked to write about.

44:04.669 --> 44:07.237
Even though I have a
million wishes for me,

44:07.239 --> 44:10.640
like being a star or a really
famous scientist...

44:10.642 --> 44:11.574
[ Laughs ]

44:11.576 --> 44:13.410
I wished for the health
and well-being

44:13.412 --> 44:15.745
of all the children
in the world.

44:15.747 --> 44:20.717
It's weird. It's like it
just wrote itself.

44:20.719 --> 44:22.819
[ Vacuum whirring ]

44:27.058 --> 44:29.292
[ Whirring stops ]

45:23.414 --> 45:27.083
[ Overlapping chatter ]

45:27.085 --> 45:28.685
Yeah.

45:28.687 --> 45:30.954
Hey, Eddie.

45:32.890 --> 45:34.124
John. You okay?

45:34.126 --> 45:37.160
I'm gonna build you a hospital,

45:37.162 --> 45:38.828
a children's hospital.

45:40.164 --> 45:42.899
How much will that cost?

45:45.536 --> 45:47.537
Nothing would make me happier,
John,

45:47.539 --> 45:51.508
but, uh, I'd better explain
a couple things.

45:51.510 --> 45:52.942
Okay.

45:54.145 --> 45:56.379
Why don't we go inside
out of the cold?

46:01.886 --> 46:03.887
[ Crickets chirping ]

46:09.393 --> 46:11.794
[ Radio ] ...Figure out
what to do next.

46:11.796 --> 46:13.263
[ Buzzer ]

46:13.265 --> 46:14.731
encouraged by Friday's report.

46:14.733 --> 46:16.833
Obviously it was better than
the market expected.

46:16.835 --> 46:18.334
Brenda: Hello.

46:18.336 --> 46:21.571
Hi. Uh, Brenda?

46:21.573 --> 46:22.906
Yes.

46:22.908 --> 46:24.774
Hi. Bruce Komiski.

46:26.644 --> 46:27.677
Uh-huh.

46:27.679 --> 46:31.614
Yeah. John invited
me to dinner.

46:31.616 --> 46:33.750
Oh, uh...

46:33.752 --> 46:35.084
Right. Right.

46:35.086 --> 46:37.120
Uh, let me open the gate, okay?

46:37.122 --> 46:38.955
Give me a second.

46:46.096 --> 46:48.097
You've reached John Fareri.
Damn it.

46:48.099 --> 46:49.099
Leave a message.

46:49.100 --> 46:50.934
John, w-where are you,

46:50.936 --> 46:53.036
and who is Bruce?

46:58.542 --> 47:00.009
Brenda: Have a seat.

47:00.011 --> 47:01.311
Oh, thank you.

47:01.313 --> 47:02.679
Would you like a glass of wine?

47:02.681 --> 47:04.547
Red or white? Sure.
Whatever's open.

47:04.549 --> 47:07.717
Okay. All right. I'll just...
I'll be back in one second.

47:07.719 --> 47:08.719
All right.

47:23.667 --> 47:24.701
Ah.

47:24.703 --> 47:26.736
Here we are.

47:26.738 --> 47:28.738
Thank you. Great.

47:28.740 --> 47:30.173
Cheers. Cheers.

47:33.043 --> 47:36.346
So John's probably just having
one of those crazy
days at work.

47:36.348 --> 47:38.581
I'm sure he'll be right
along any minute.

47:38.583 --> 47:39.583
Great.

47:44.154 --> 47:45.488
I'm sorry for your loss.

47:47.057 --> 47:48.057
Thanks.

47:52.863 --> 47:56.966
Unusually, uh, warm for
this time of year?

47:56.968 --> 47:58.368
You know how it is.

47:58.370 --> 48:01.170
It could snow tomorrow or
the next day or...

48:01.172 --> 48:03.206
Right. Funny.

48:03.208 --> 48:04.507
Heh.

48:04.509 --> 48:06.342
That... this is good.

48:06.344 --> 48:07.477
What is it?

48:07.479 --> 48:09.912
Uh, I forget.

48:09.914 --> 48:11.381
I'll go get the bottle.

48:11.383 --> 48:13.716
You know, it's... it's
not important.

48:13.718 --> 48:15.785
No? Okay.

48:16.787 --> 48:17.787
You know what?

48:19.623 --> 48:21.991
I think it actually did
snow last year

48:21.993 --> 48:23.059
right around this time.

48:23.061 --> 48:24.294
Huh.

48:24.296 --> 48:27.797
The weather these days...

48:27.799 --> 48:29.799
Oh.

48:29.801 --> 48:30.801
John.

48:33.203 --> 48:34.671
[ Bottle cap pops ]

48:34.673 --> 48:36.372
Bruce? What are you doing here?

48:36.374 --> 48:37.907
Dinner.

48:37.909 --> 48:39.809
Remember?

48:39.811 --> 48:40.910
Yeah. Yeah.

48:40.912 --> 48:42.245
Oh. [ Chuckles ]

48:42.247 --> 48:43.546
Yeah, sure.

48:43.548 --> 48:45.148
Brenda and I, we got a chance

48:45.150 --> 48:46.316
to get to know one another.

48:46.318 --> 48:48.685
You two have already met, right?

48:48.687 --> 48:49.919
No.

48:49.921 --> 48:51.587
No? No, John.

48:52.690 --> 48:54.824
John: So how was your first
day on the job?

48:54.826 --> 48:56.826
Well, I, uh, got to the
medical center,

48:56.828 --> 48:59.262
and I introduced myself to
the head of planning,

48:59.264 --> 49:01.497
and I... I told her that
I was in charge

49:01.499 --> 49:03.066
of the new hospital project,

49:03.068 --> 49:04.801
and, um... and she said,

49:04.803 --> 49:07.236
if there was such a thing,
that would be her job.

49:07.238 --> 49:09.672
Yeah, yeah. She thinks it is.

49:09.674 --> 49:12.775
Yeah. So I then went to Eddie
Stolzenberg's office,

49:12.777 --> 49:14.510
and, um... and he said, "yeah,
yeah, no.

49:14.512 --> 49:16.012
"You don't want to tell
anybody, you know,

49:16.014 --> 49:18.448
what you're doing or... or
why you're here."

49:18.450 --> 49:19.882
[ Chuckles ]

49:19.884 --> 49:23.119
So, I mean, he is...
he does have

49:23.121 --> 49:24.520
the authority
to... to build this?

49:24.522 --> 49:27.090
Oh, yeah, he thinks he does,
yeah.

49:27.092 --> 49:29.592
I mean, you know, I, um...

49:29.594 --> 49:32.595
I left my job, and I
moved my stuff here.

49:32.597 --> 49:34.130
If I don't really have a job...

49:34.132 --> 49:35.132
no, you have a job.

49:35.133 --> 49:37.033
I... I hired you.

49:37.035 --> 49:38.434
Uh-huh.

49:38.436 --> 49:40.703
I mean, usually, the
board hires me.

49:40.705 --> 49:43.005
I don't have a board.

49:43.007 --> 49:43.940
Should I get a board?

49:43.942 --> 49:46.409
Bruce, would you like
some more wine?

49:46.411 --> 49:47.944
Yes, please.

50:01.058 --> 50:03.993
Well, he seems very nice.

50:03.995 --> 50:05.161
Yeah.

50:05.163 --> 50:08.231
But do you think you could try
to remember to tell me

50:08.233 --> 50:11.367
the next time you invite
somebody over for dinner?

50:11.369 --> 50:13.870
I mean, I'm... I'm glad you
had someone over

50:13.872 --> 50:16.472
and that we had dinner together.

50:16.474 --> 50:18.674
[ Crickets chirping ]

50:26.450 --> 50:28.651
[ Bell tolling ]

50:30.220 --> 50:31.454
Lydia.

50:31.456 --> 50:33.222
John...

50:35.092 --> 50:37.226
Sorry about your loss.

50:37.228 --> 50:39.862
Well, thank you. Thank you.

50:39.864 --> 50:41.464
Uh,

50:41.466 --> 50:44.567
I was wondering if
you've heard about

50:44.569 --> 50:46.569
this project that
I'm working on.

50:46.571 --> 50:47.571
The hospital?

50:47.572 --> 50:49.038
Yeah. Yeah.

50:49.040 --> 50:52.041
Um, I was hoping

50:52.043 --> 50:55.244
that I could have your
support on it.

50:57.114 --> 51:01.617
Honestly, I don't think I can
be much help to you on that.

51:01.619 --> 51:04.086
The folks I have influence with

51:04.088 --> 51:06.789
are just too suspicious of you,
John.

51:06.791 --> 51:08.825
Sorry.

51:42.326 --> 51:43.493
You gotta be kidding.

51:43.495 --> 51:45.061
Really, it was awful.

51:45.063 --> 51:50.433
Apparently, dad talked this guy
into leaving a real job.

51:50.435 --> 51:51.634
Is this some kind of
cut-rate deck?

51:51.636 --> 51:53.703
Oh, listen to her.

51:53.705 --> 51:56.372
Whoa, don't bet outside
your comfort zone.

51:56.374 --> 51:57.673
I'll raise you. Okay.

51:57.675 --> 51:59.642
This guy, by the end
of the evening,

51:59.644 --> 52:00.943
he had this look on his face,

52:00.945 --> 52:02.678
you know, like the
environmentalists get

52:02.680 --> 52:04.847
when they realize that dad has
done a number on them?

52:04.849 --> 52:06.549
Sounds like the old dad.

52:06.551 --> 52:07.817
Yeah.

52:07.819 --> 52:10.119
Is he getting anywhere
with this hospital?

52:10.121 --> 52:11.020
Uh, whew.

52:11.022 --> 52:12.788
I... you know, I don't
really know.

52:12.790 --> 52:14.156
He doesn't talk to me about it.

52:14.158 --> 52:16.325
It's weird. He's normally
such a chatterbox.

52:17.995 --> 52:20.263
Well, it's good he
has a project.

52:20.265 --> 52:21.265
Yes, yes. Yeah.

52:21.266 --> 52:22.632
Yeah, yeah.

52:22.634 --> 52:24.333
Fantasy of some hospital

52:24.335 --> 52:25.601
so he can wipe out the memories

52:25.603 --> 52:27.436
of what happened to Maria
at the old one

52:27.438 --> 52:28.838
and, uh, forget the
family he has left.

52:28.840 --> 52:30.139
Michael. Okay, Michael.

52:30.141 --> 52:32.808
What? It's like none of
us even exist.

52:32.810 --> 52:35.945
Michael, everyone that loses
someone goes through this.

52:37.781 --> 52:40.116
We just have to stick together.

52:43.220 --> 52:44.820
Whose bet is it?

52:46.590 --> 52:49.125
Mine.

52:51.361 --> 52:53.396
[ Siren blaring ]

53:01.438 --> 53:02.838
Steph.

53:04.441 --> 53:05.975
You there?

53:28.465 --> 53:30.399
Needless to say, we
love the idea.

53:30.401 --> 53:31.901
We're... we're 100% behind it.

53:31.903 --> 53:33.769
It's a beautiful thing,
what you're doing.

53:33.771 --> 53:35.571
Especially with everything that
you've been through.

53:35.573 --> 53:38.975
Okay. What do you
need me to do?

53:40.210 --> 53:42.178
Well, the thing is...

53:42.180 --> 53:45.748
I'm not a patient you're
giving bad news to.

53:45.750 --> 53:47.950
It's all right. You can just...

53:47.952 --> 53:48.751
what?

53:48.753 --> 53:51.420
All right. Well, how do I...

53:51.422 --> 53:52.588
how do I put this? Um,

53:52.590 --> 53:54.790
despite everybody loving kids

53:54.792 --> 53:57.093
and how they're our... our
future and everything,

53:57.095 --> 54:02.465
uh, pediatrics is the bottom
of the food chain,

54:02.467 --> 54:03.799
neurosurgeons, the
transplant guys

54:03.801 --> 54:05.768
being the big guns around here

54:05.770 --> 54:07.136
since they bring in the money.

54:07.138 --> 54:09.205
Now, they are not happy
with your idea,

54:09.207 --> 54:11.774
because they're like, "well,
we want a new toy.

54:11.776 --> 54:13.209
"We want a gamma knife.

54:13.211 --> 54:15.311
We don't want a
children's hospital."

54:15.313 --> 54:18.581
So they've gone to bitch to all
of their friends at the
county legislature,

54:18.583 --> 54:19.949
who unfortunately
are our bosses,

54:19.951 --> 54:22.151
and they're not happy with
your idea either,

54:22.153 --> 54:23.886
because they don't
want to take on

54:23.888 --> 54:25.488
any big capital projects during
an election cycle.

54:25.490 --> 54:28.157
Their biggest donors, who don't
want to lose any business,

54:28.159 --> 54:30.226
they don't want you stealing
any of their business...

54:30.228 --> 54:31.927
[ Overlapping ] ...State
board of health

54:31.929 --> 54:33.829
which has to approve any
construction of new hospitals.

54:33.831 --> 54:35.665
They don't want you taking
their business.

54:35.667 --> 54:37.566
And a lot of these S.O.B.s...

54:37.568 --> 54:38.934
construction on a new hospital.

54:38.936 --> 54:40.136
Did I leave anything out?

54:40.138 --> 54:42.505
Money.

54:42.507 --> 54:45.975
Yeah, nobody's mentioned where
would the money come from.

54:45.977 --> 54:48.644
Okay. We finished?

54:48.646 --> 54:49.812
That's not enough?

54:49.814 --> 54:51.847
Bruce found a fund-raiser.

54:51.849 --> 54:53.849
I'll speak to the state senator.

54:53.851 --> 54:56.152
It's all good.

55:00.957 --> 55:03.993
Courage, compassion, devotion,
destiny.

55:04.795 --> 55:07.730
What do you think?

55:07.732 --> 55:10.633
It's wonderful, Michael.

55:11.702 --> 55:13.769
It's so big.

55:13.771 --> 55:15.905
That must have hurt quite a lot.

55:15.907 --> 55:17.773
Lot less than laying around,
trying to figure out

55:17.775 --> 55:20.042
how long it would take to
flunk out. Heh.

55:20.044 --> 55:21.944
I'm gonna go for a walk.

55:29.653 --> 55:31.087
[ Sighs ]

55:31.089 --> 55:32.788
I'm trying to take care of him.

55:32.790 --> 55:35.057
I know. I know you are.

55:35.059 --> 55:36.859
At least I've got my classes

55:36.861 --> 55:39.261
to get my mind off things,
but he's...

55:45.168 --> 55:47.603
did you ever try to talk to
dad about things?

55:47.605 --> 55:50.039
Dad?

55:50.041 --> 55:54.043
I just have to be strong for
him until he comes out of it.

55:54.045 --> 55:58.147
Yeah, but what if he doesn't?

55:58.149 --> 55:59.415
He will.

55:59.417 --> 56:01.183
I know he will.

56:02.452 --> 56:05.654
It's just weird.

56:05.656 --> 56:07.890
For the first time in my life,

56:07.892 --> 56:09.892
I'm realizing he's
not our father.

56:09.894 --> 56:12.728
He is, Julie. He
always has been.

56:12.730 --> 56:13.730
I know.

56:13.731 --> 56:15.931
I keep telling myself that,

56:15.933 --> 56:19.368
but now it's like he
could just disappear

56:19.370 --> 56:22.138
and it'll be like it was
before he came along,

56:22.140 --> 56:23.539
like we were never a family.

56:23.541 --> 56:25.107
Don't say that!

56:26.676 --> 56:29.812
I've always been able
to count on you.

56:29.814 --> 56:31.947
I'm sorry.

56:31.949 --> 56:33.649
I'm trying.

56:36.553 --> 56:38.621
I'm really trying.

57:07.017 --> 57:08.517
[ Maria laughs ]

57:32.709 --> 57:36.245
Well, I'm amazed that you have
the strength to pursue this

57:36.247 --> 57:37.880
after what you've been through,

57:37.882 --> 57:39.715
losing your only child.

57:39.717 --> 57:41.617
She's not my only child.

57:41.619 --> 57:44.386
I'm sorry. I meant your only...

57:44.388 --> 57:46.822
I'm just saying it's a
beautiful thing,

57:46.824 --> 57:47.990
what you're trying to do,

57:47.992 --> 57:49.959
but it is a big lift.

57:49.961 --> 57:51.794
It's not gonna be all Kumbaya.

57:51.796 --> 57:53.729
I've been trying to
tell him that.

57:53.731 --> 57:55.364
John, you're a developer, right?

57:55.366 --> 57:58.767
You see a piece of property,
you go, "what's this cost?"

57:58.769 --> 58:00.069
Then you pull a few strings.

58:00.071 --> 58:01.570
You bend a few rules.

58:01.572 --> 58:03.138
A year later, the job is done.

58:03.140 --> 58:04.874
The government's not like that.

58:04.876 --> 58:08.344
In politics, you have to hold a
very high standard of
low expectations.

58:08.346 --> 58:09.445
Let's say the
county's behind it,

58:09.447 --> 58:11.146
but some jerks in the
legislature,

58:11.148 --> 58:12.615
they're opposed to it,

58:12.617 --> 58:14.483
because they... they got some
kind of pet project.

58:14.485 --> 58:16.252
Yeah, or the
legislature's in favor,

58:16.254 --> 58:19.255
but the division of
budget kills it.

58:19.257 --> 58:22.558
I mean, I don't want to say
anything, but...

58:22.560 --> 58:23.560
Say it.

58:25.829 --> 58:27.429
We both know

58:27.431 --> 58:29.732
you made one or two
enemies along the way.

58:29.734 --> 58:34.036
Come on. It's not like I'm
trying to build a strip club.

58:34.038 --> 58:35.971
I know.

58:35.973 --> 58:39.475
Like I said, it's a
beautiful thing.

58:39.477 --> 58:41.343
I'm just saying.

58:45.548 --> 58:48.751
John: No family should have to
endure what we did.

58:48.753 --> 58:50.152
This is just a no-brainer.

58:50.154 --> 58:51.887
You've got people around here
taking their kids

58:51.889 --> 58:53.522
to a hospital that's...
it's a nightmare.

58:53.524 --> 58:56.458
I mean, you gotta be able to
raise money to fix that, right?

58:56.460 --> 58:58.494
Woman: I wish I had better
news to tell you,

58:58.496 --> 59:02.064
but unfortunately the numbers
just don't add up.

59:02.066 --> 59:04.800
We've looked at it from
several different angles.

59:04.802 --> 59:06.468
And this is what it is.

59:06.470 --> 59:09.371
So say you need 120
million to build this.

59:09.373 --> 59:11.941
130 by the time you're done.

59:11.943 --> 59:14.510
So to issue bonds for this,

59:14.512 --> 59:18.013
you need donations of at
least 25 million.

59:18.015 --> 59:19.415
Right, yeah.

59:19.417 --> 59:21.717
Unfortunately, our study shows

59:21.719 --> 59:23.953
that you'd be lucky to raise 10.

59:23.955 --> 59:26.288
10? This is the richest
part of the country.

59:26.290 --> 59:28.357
Trouble is you have
no donor base.

59:28.359 --> 59:30.526
This is a county facility.

59:30.528 --> 59:33.228
People feel like they've done
more than their share

59:33.230 --> 59:34.797
by just paying their taxes.

59:34.799 --> 59:36.699
What about, um, a
corporate sponsor?

59:36.701 --> 59:39.468
Maybe, if you let them put
their name on it.

59:39.470 --> 59:40.703
They might contribute something.

59:40.705 --> 59:41.904
Exactly.

59:41.906 --> 59:43.505
Maria's name is going on it.

59:43.507 --> 59:45.708
What? Maria's name is
going on it.

59:45.710 --> 59:47.443
Right.

59:48.678 --> 59:51.480
Well, I wish you luck.

59:55.018 --> 59:57.152
Thank you for your time.

01:00:00.523 --> 01:00:03.192
All right, um...

01:00:05.462 --> 01:00:09.164
Maybe... maybe you should
rethink this.

01:00:09.166 --> 01:00:10.733
Rethink what?

01:00:10.735 --> 01:00:12.234
Aren't you listening to
anything anyone has to say?

01:00:12.236 --> 01:00:13.602
What's the point?

01:00:13.604 --> 01:00:14.803
What's the point?

01:00:14.805 --> 01:00:16.005
They're just saying no.

01:00:16.007 --> 01:00:18.240
Why do you think that is?

01:00:20.910 --> 01:00:22.711
[ Sighs ]

01:00:22.713 --> 01:00:24.179
You want to quit?

01:00:37.761 --> 01:00:39.895
Thanks for dinner. It was good.

01:00:41.364 --> 01:00:43.065
John.

01:00:43.067 --> 01:00:45.434
Yeah?

01:00:46.803 --> 01:00:48.670
I want to be involved.

01:00:51.207 --> 01:00:52.808
With the hospital.

01:00:52.810 --> 01:00:54.276
I want to help.

01:00:56.946 --> 01:00:59.214
You don't... you don't need me?

01:00:59.216 --> 01:01:01.417
You want to do it all...
all by yourself?

01:01:01.419 --> 01:01:03.986
What are you talking about?
I have Bruce.

01:01:12.462 --> 01:01:13.796
Jesus.

01:01:15.165 --> 01:01:16.899
She was my daughter, too!

01:01:18.468 --> 01:01:22.204
You are not the only one
who feels hurt!

01:01:22.206 --> 01:01:25.140
You have three other children!

01:01:25.142 --> 01:01:27.843
Do you even care what
they're going through?

01:01:39.823 --> 01:01:41.256
Say something.

01:01:47.664 --> 01:01:49.631
[ Crying ]

01:01:53.937 --> 01:01:57.106
I can't do this anymore.

01:01:57.108 --> 01:02:00.976
I can't... I can't be strong
for you anymore.

01:02:00.978 --> 01:02:02.845
I can't do it.

01:02:02.847 --> 01:02:04.847
[ Fragments crunching ]

01:02:24.334 --> 01:02:27.002
Maria: Adults are so weird.

01:02:30.273 --> 01:02:34.476
Mom told me it scares her when
dad doesn't talk to her,

01:02:34.478 --> 01:02:37.779
because when she was little,
her mother would get mad

01:02:37.781 --> 01:02:42.351
and wouldn't talk to her for
weeks, literally.

01:02:43.620 --> 01:02:46.355
But she doesn't want
dad to know that,

01:02:46.357 --> 01:02:48.257
because she thinks it
would freak him out

01:02:48.259 --> 01:02:49.758
or piss him off or something.

01:02:53.263 --> 01:02:56.498
But maybe dad doesn't
talk sometimes

01:02:56.500 --> 01:03:00.502
because actions speak
louder than words.

01:03:12.048 --> 01:03:13.782
John?

01:03:13.784 --> 01:03:15.951
Yeah, it's me.

01:03:20.056 --> 01:03:22.791
Where have I been?

01:03:22.793 --> 01:03:25.360
I don't know.

01:03:25.362 --> 01:03:27.696
I don't know either.

01:03:29.165 --> 01:03:30.699
I'm sorry.

01:03:33.169 --> 01:03:35.437
I'm sorry, too.

01:04:30.693 --> 01:04:35.430
How long have you been
building hospitals?

01:04:35.432 --> 01:04:38.066
Well, gee, it's been
about 17 years now.

01:04:38.068 --> 01:04:39.434
Yeah? More or less.

01:04:48.177 --> 01:04:50.912
Ready?

01:04:50.914 --> 01:04:52.281
Uh, I don't know.

01:04:52.283 --> 01:04:54.116
I really don't know about this.

01:04:54.118 --> 01:04:55.118
Want to cancel?

01:04:55.119 --> 01:04:56.119
Maybe.

01:04:56.120 --> 01:04:57.252
Yeah? Okay. No, no, no.

01:04:57.254 --> 01:04:58.420
I don't know.

01:04:58.422 --> 01:05:00.956
You know, I don't know either.
No.

01:05:00.958 --> 01:05:04.159
I mean, I've never done
fund-raising in my life.

01:05:04.161 --> 01:05:05.193
Oh, no? No.

01:05:05.195 --> 01:05:07.562
No, but the consultant told me

01:05:07.564 --> 01:05:09.064
that there's nothing more fun

01:05:09.066 --> 01:05:12.267
than looking someone in the
eye, asking for money

01:05:12.269 --> 01:05:13.702
and watching them squirm.

01:05:13.704 --> 01:05:16.204
That sounds like a nightmare.

01:05:16.206 --> 01:05:17.639
Heh.

01:05:17.641 --> 01:05:18.974
Right.

01:05:20.510 --> 01:05:23.512
So can anyone tell me
what this is?

01:05:23.514 --> 01:05:26.315
Um, a basement room?

01:05:26.317 --> 01:05:28.617
Anyone else?

01:05:28.619 --> 01:05:30.719
Now, I... I gather
that none of you

01:05:30.721 --> 01:05:33.288
have had the occasion to be in
a place like this,

01:05:33.290 --> 01:05:34.556
and, hopefully, you won't,

01:05:34.558 --> 01:05:35.991
because it's a
low-security prison cell.

01:05:35.993 --> 01:05:39.461
Now here, here is a place
that we're all likely

01:05:39.463 --> 01:05:43.298
to end up in at some point,
a hospital room.

01:05:43.300 --> 01:05:50.305
Now, what's amazing to me is
how similar these
two rooms are.

01:05:50.307 --> 01:05:51.640
You take a person.

01:05:51.642 --> 01:05:54.376
You take their clothes.

01:05:54.378 --> 01:05:56.578
You assign them a number.

01:05:56.580 --> 01:05:58.747
You put them in a room
with a stranger.

01:05:58.749 --> 01:06:00.716
You give them
institutional food.

01:06:00.718 --> 01:06:04.486
It's the most dehumanizing
thing you can possibly
do to a person,

01:06:04.488 --> 01:06:08.023
and we do it at the worst
moment of your life.

01:06:08.025 --> 01:06:12.194
We do it when you're sick
or you're dying.

01:06:15.898 --> 01:06:19.334
Do you want to... do you want
to just say a few...

01:06:19.336 --> 01:06:20.402
now? Yeah.

01:06:20.404 --> 01:06:22.504
Okay.

01:06:22.506 --> 01:06:23.972
[ Clears throat ]

01:06:27.910 --> 01:06:30.712
Um...

01:06:30.714 --> 01:06:34.583
Everything that Bruce just said.

01:06:34.585 --> 01:06:38.687
Uh, we want to build a place

01:06:38.689 --> 01:06:43.058
where there's enough room for
children to get well

01:06:43.060 --> 01:06:49.064
and where parents aren't
sleeping in chairs in
the hallways.

01:06:52.368 --> 01:06:54.002
Has cut its earnings,

01:06:54.004 --> 01:06:56.004
recorded a
fourth-quarter charge,

01:06:56.006 --> 01:06:57.038
dismissed its auditors

01:06:57.040 --> 01:06:59.107
and suffered an
embarrassing 3%...

01:06:59.109 --> 01:07:02.577
And here we are. Okay.

01:07:04.981 --> 01:07:07.182
Well, your prison
thing was great.

01:07:07.184 --> 01:07:09.317
Oh, thank you.

01:07:09.319 --> 01:07:10.385
I was awful.

01:07:10.387 --> 01:07:12.053
No, come on. You were great.

01:07:12.055 --> 01:07:13.355
No. Yeah.

01:07:13.357 --> 01:07:15.290
I didn't... I didn't
know what to say.

01:07:15.292 --> 01:07:19.594
I haven't... I haven't really
talked to anyone since...

01:07:25.468 --> 01:07:27.402
I'm sorry. Hmm.

01:07:27.404 --> 01:07:30.605
John's idea of
bringing me on board

01:07:30.607 --> 01:07:32.007
was to dump me on you.

01:07:32.009 --> 01:07:33.341
Oh, no.

01:07:33.343 --> 01:07:36.077
I know babysitting a...

01:07:36.079 --> 01:07:37.746
Grief-stricken basket case

01:07:37.748 --> 01:07:40.282
doesn't exactly fit your
job description.

01:07:40.284 --> 01:07:41.850
Actually it does pretty much.

01:07:41.852 --> 01:07:42.651
Oh.

01:07:42.653 --> 01:07:44.853
[ Both laugh ]

01:07:46.022 --> 01:07:47.989
You're sweet.

01:07:47.991 --> 01:07:48.991
Good night.

01:07:48.992 --> 01:07:50.659
Good night.

01:07:50.661 --> 01:07:53.595
[ Crickets chirping ]

01:07:53.597 --> 01:07:55.797
[ Cellphone buzzing ]

01:08:07.143 --> 01:08:08.443
[ Cellphone beeps ]

01:08:08.445 --> 01:08:10.645
[ Line ringing ]

01:08:11.747 --> 01:08:13.915
You have not reached us,

01:08:13.917 --> 01:08:18.353
so I'll call you back. [ Beep ]

01:08:18.354 --> 01:08:21.890
[ Train horn honks ]

01:08:24.460 --> 01:08:27.729
[ Indistinct announcement ]

01:08:32.868 --> 01:08:35.002
Hey, sweetie, I don't know if
you have plans tonight,

01:08:35.005 --> 01:08:37.973
but if you're free, dad and I
are going over to
meet some donors,

01:08:37.975 --> 01:08:40.542
and it would be so great if
you guys could come.

01:08:40.544 --> 01:08:42.143
It's something we can
all do together.

01:08:42.145 --> 01:08:43.145
What do you think?

01:08:43.145 --> 01:08:44.912
Oh, I'm sorry.

01:08:44.915 --> 01:08:46.814
I've got a paper due Monday,

01:08:46.817 --> 01:08:48.716
but if I get that under control,

01:08:48.719 --> 01:08:50.085
we were gonna go see some
friends tonight.

01:08:50.087 --> 01:08:52.386
Well, we don't want to mess
up your weekend.

01:08:52.389 --> 01:08:54.389
It's just so nice to
see you two.

01:08:54.390 --> 01:08:56.457
Try to get Steph to come home,

01:08:56.460 --> 01:08:58.560
but you know how she is.

01:08:58.562 --> 01:09:00.028
Yeah.

01:09:00.029 --> 01:09:02.029
Well, this is the design.
Came in last week.

01:09:02.032 --> 01:09:04.666
Dad's hired some really
great architects

01:09:04.667 --> 01:09:06.734
who've done a lot of hospitals.

01:09:06.737 --> 01:09:08.970
Julie: Great. That's
really great.

01:09:08.971 --> 01:09:12.607
I mean, that's just a
preliminary idea, right?

01:09:12.609 --> 01:09:13.808
Yeah, it's fine.

01:09:13.810 --> 01:09:16.578
Just wonder where you
guys will be at

01:09:16.580 --> 01:09:19.346
if you ever finish this
memorial to Maria.

01:09:20.515 --> 01:09:22.450
It's not a memorial.

01:09:25.220 --> 01:09:26.854
Maria is dead, dad.

01:09:26.857 --> 01:09:28.823
She's dead. Mike...

01:09:28.825 --> 01:09:30.358
I... look, I don't need you

01:09:30.359 --> 01:09:31.493
telling me what I can say.

01:09:31.495 --> 01:09:32.493
I'm not telling you... you are.

01:09:32.496 --> 01:09:34.296
Stop it!

01:09:34.298 --> 01:09:37.799
Oh, and God forbid we upset
mom, because she can't take it.

01:09:37.801 --> 01:09:40.502
Hey, don't talk about your
mother like that.

01:09:40.504 --> 01:09:42.069
Oh, now you're the
perfect husband?

01:09:43.272 --> 01:09:44.639
Where have you been?

01:09:44.640 --> 01:09:46.774
You don't know what goes
on between us.

01:09:46.777 --> 01:09:49.344
Right. You're right.

01:09:49.345 --> 01:09:50.745
Don't worry about mom.

01:09:50.747 --> 01:09:52.212
Don't worry about Steph,

01:09:52.215 --> 01:09:53.582
wherever she is out there.

01:09:53.584 --> 01:09:55.483
Just keep building
your glass box.

01:09:55.485 --> 01:09:58.053
That'll make
everything all right.

01:10:28.784 --> 01:10:30.986
[ Indistinct announcement ]

01:10:34.724 --> 01:10:36.524
Bye, sweetie.

01:10:38.794 --> 01:10:40.595
Bye, honey.

01:10:40.597 --> 01:10:42.230
Bye.

01:10:42.232 --> 01:10:43.232
What?

01:10:43.233 --> 01:10:44.233
Heh.

01:10:47.570 --> 01:10:49.204
Steph call?

01:10:49.206 --> 01:10:50.705
No,

01:10:50.707 --> 01:10:53.875
and I'm really starting to
freak out about that.

01:10:58.648 --> 01:11:00.649
We've been calling her for days.

01:11:00.651 --> 01:11:02.651
Sometimes we're able to
leave messages.

01:11:02.653 --> 01:11:04.052
Sometimes it just rings.

01:11:04.054 --> 01:11:06.321
The last time you talked to
her, she was where?

01:11:06.323 --> 01:11:08.189
San Francisco.

01:11:08.191 --> 01:11:10.759
And that was a friendly
conversation?

01:11:10.761 --> 01:11:12.494
[ Cellphone chimes ]

01:11:16.565 --> 01:11:18.667
Oh! Oh, thank God!

01:11:18.669 --> 01:11:19.868
Is that her?

01:11:20.703 --> 01:11:22.003
All right.

01:11:22.005 --> 01:11:24.305
I'm so sorry. She
just hates us.

01:11:24.307 --> 01:11:26.641
She's just... she's
always been very...

01:11:26.643 --> 01:11:29.811
That's great. I mean,
that she's okay.

01:11:29.813 --> 01:11:31.446
I'm so sorry. All right,
no worries.

01:11:31.448 --> 01:11:32.514
My pleasure. Thank you.

01:11:32.516 --> 01:11:34.249
Can... can we get you
some coffee?

01:11:34.251 --> 01:11:35.251
No. It's okay.

01:11:35.252 --> 01:11:36.451
A sandwich?

01:11:36.453 --> 01:11:38.453
No, really. I-I'm fine, thanks.

01:11:39.488 --> 01:11:40.989
[ Overlapping chatter ]

01:11:40.991 --> 01:11:44.526
Maria, she really cared
about people,

01:11:44.528 --> 01:11:46.795
and she wanted to make
a difference.

01:11:46.797 --> 01:11:49.631
I know how that sounds. I
don't want you

01:11:49.633 --> 01:11:50.999
thinking we're these
deluded parents.

01:11:51.001 --> 01:11:52.967
I mean, she definitely had
her faults, right?

01:11:52.969 --> 01:11:54.803
Yeah, definitely.

01:11:54.805 --> 01:11:56.371
And she was, you
know... she could be

01:11:56.373 --> 01:11:58.006
very determined when she
wanted something.

01:11:58.008 --> 01:12:00.675
I mean, she was her father's
daughter, right?

01:12:00.677 --> 01:12:04.179
Her Christmas wish list, I'm...

01:12:04.181 --> 01:12:05.346
yeah.

01:12:05.348 --> 01:12:06.948
Maria: Cute tank tops,

01:12:06.950 --> 01:12:08.683
a red-hooded sweatshirt,

01:12:08.685 --> 01:12:09.751
flannel PJs,

01:12:09.753 --> 01:12:11.820
a purple LL Bean jacket,

01:12:11.822 --> 01:12:14.522
an iPod, iTunes gift cards,

01:12:14.524 --> 01:12:18.026
oh, and a puppy named Gus.

01:12:21.797 --> 01:12:24.532
Brenda: You can pick three,
okay?

01:12:26.502 --> 01:12:29.270
How? This is so depressing.

01:12:29.272 --> 01:12:33.041
I mean, what about
toys or games?

01:12:33.043 --> 01:12:35.376
Well, honey, these are
things that they need.

01:12:35.378 --> 01:12:39.447
I know, mom, but how merry is
a pair of gloves?

01:12:39.449 --> 01:12:42.851
Can we please get them some fun
stuff along with the gloves?

01:12:42.853 --> 01:12:44.352
Well, you know,
Christmas isn't about

01:12:44.354 --> 01:12:46.588
how much money you can spend.
There's a... a budget.

01:12:48.557 --> 01:12:51.226
So...

01:12:51.228 --> 01:12:53.995
What if I cut some things
off my wish list?

01:12:53.997 --> 01:12:57.031
Like, well, I don't
absolutely need a iPod.

01:12:57.033 --> 01:12:58.900
And if I cut that,

01:12:58.902 --> 01:13:01.970
I guess I won't be needing
iTunes gift cards, will I?

01:13:01.972 --> 01:13:04.005
Well, maybe a couple.

01:13:04.007 --> 01:13:07.609
I can always play them on
Lila's iPod. Yeah.

01:13:08.778 --> 01:13:11.179
Eww, don't get all weird.

01:13:11.181 --> 01:13:14.215
Oh, my gosh, you guys are so
freaking embarrassing.

01:13:14.217 --> 01:13:16.451
Ooh.

01:13:18.354 --> 01:13:20.188
What can I tell you?
She'd recently

01:13:20.190 --> 01:13:21.923
discovered the power
of the f-word.

01:13:21.925 --> 01:13:23.391
[ Chuckles ]

01:13:23.393 --> 01:13:26.127
It's really wonderful to hear
you talk about her.

01:13:30.733 --> 01:13:31.966
Yeah.

01:13:40.109 --> 01:13:42.911
Did they... did they
say a million?

01:13:42.913 --> 01:13:44.546
They were talking about
dollars, right?

01:13:44.548 --> 01:13:45.814
Shh. Oh, my God.

01:13:45.816 --> 01:13:47.315
All right.

01:13:47.317 --> 01:13:48.317
Yes!

01:13:48.318 --> 01:13:49.150
Shh. I'm sorry.

01:13:49.152 --> 01:13:50.352
[ Laughs ] Shh, shh, shh, shh.

01:13:55.391 --> 01:13:56.558
How's it going?

01:13:56.560 --> 01:13:57.759
It's all right.

01:13:57.761 --> 01:14:00.128
I found something.

01:14:00.130 --> 01:14:02.697
Maria wanted me to use it

01:14:02.699 --> 01:14:04.699
in the kitchen at the
Gimbel estate.

01:14:04.701 --> 01:14:05.800
[ Chuckles ]

01:14:05.802 --> 01:14:07.602
Yeah. That's what I thought.

01:14:07.604 --> 01:14:08.636
Maria: "rose carmethene."

01:14:08.638 --> 01:14:10.438
That's so cool.

01:14:10.440 --> 01:14:13.341
Mm, not for a kitchen.

01:14:13.343 --> 01:14:15.009
That's too loud.

01:14:15.011 --> 01:14:17.979
What's wrong with a
loud kitchen?

01:14:17.981 --> 01:14:21.516
Kitchens should be, you know...

01:14:21.518 --> 01:14:22.650
Quiet?

01:14:22.652 --> 01:14:24.319
Right.

01:14:24.321 --> 01:14:25.386
Who says?

01:14:25.388 --> 01:14:26.521
You did.

01:14:28.657 --> 01:14:30.525
Beige isn't everything.

01:14:30.527 --> 01:14:33.494
[ Laughs ]

01:14:33.496 --> 01:14:35.630
Bye-bye, rose carmethene.

01:14:35.632 --> 01:14:37.198
[ Kiss ]

01:14:39.168 --> 01:14:40.168
Heh heh.

01:14:40.170 --> 01:14:42.604
I just thought it was
interesting.

01:15:03.993 --> 01:15:05.460
John.

01:15:16.906 --> 01:15:19.107
[ Crayon scratching ]

01:15:22.711 --> 01:15:24.212
You okay?

01:15:24.214 --> 01:15:26.714
Yeah. I just couldn't sleep.

01:15:37.793 --> 01:15:39.527
Wow.

01:15:41.730 --> 01:15:43.431
You know I can't draw.

01:15:44.466 --> 01:15:46.901
I'm gonna... I'm
gonna mess it up.

01:15:46.903 --> 01:15:48.403
It's a mess already.

01:15:48.405 --> 01:15:50.371
Have at it.

01:16:00.149 --> 01:16:02.817
I didn't know you
were big on puce.

01:16:02.819 --> 01:16:06.120
This is not puce. This, is,
um...

01:16:06.122 --> 01:16:09.324
this is Jazzberry jam,
I'll have you know.

01:16:09.326 --> 01:16:10.758
One of your favorites?

01:16:10.760 --> 01:16:12.226
No, no. My favorite...

01:16:13.362 --> 01:16:14.562
Is beaver.

01:16:14.564 --> 01:16:15.830
[ Both laugh ]

01:16:15.832 --> 01:16:18.166
John, this is a
children's hospital.

01:16:18.168 --> 01:16:20.368
Okay, give me my beaver back.

01:16:25.641 --> 01:16:27.275
It's not a Valentine.

01:16:27.277 --> 01:16:29.077
Come on. You said I
couldn't mess it up.

01:16:29.079 --> 01:16:30.745
It's a window.

01:16:30.747 --> 01:16:31.913
But it's too expensive.

01:16:31.915 --> 01:16:33.982
It would not come up to code.

01:16:33.984 --> 01:16:35.183
Screw code.

01:16:48.564 --> 01:16:50.231
[ Chuckles ]

01:16:52.234 --> 01:16:54.569
Oh, oh. I spilled some wine
on the hospital.

01:16:54.571 --> 01:16:55.636
Oh, Jesus.

01:16:55.638 --> 01:16:57.038
Crayons for everyone.

01:16:57.040 --> 01:16:58.906
Right. Jazzberry jam.

01:17:00.776 --> 01:17:02.076
What is with the rooster?

01:17:02.078 --> 01:17:03.177
It's a Turkey!

01:17:03.179 --> 01:17:04.212
[ Both laugh ]

01:17:04.214 --> 01:17:06.247
It's not a rooster.

01:17:09.585 --> 01:17:10.752
[ Laughs ]

01:17:12.654 --> 01:17:14.522
Yeah, no.

01:17:14.524 --> 01:17:17.692
So you can't see what they're...

01:17:22.164 --> 01:17:23.765
Looks like a ship.

01:17:28.070 --> 01:17:30.071
Cover that yet? We'll
just have to...

01:17:30.073 --> 01:17:32.673
[ Both laugh ]

01:17:34.843 --> 01:17:35.843
I've tried.

01:17:45.988 --> 01:17:48.556
The Muskwa River stretches out

01:17:48.558 --> 01:17:50.224
over an impressive 112 Miles.

01:17:50.226 --> 01:17:52.260
Eat, Mike.

01:17:52.262 --> 01:17:53.694
You should eat.

01:17:53.696 --> 01:17:56.764
Muskwa offers something
for everyone,

01:17:56.766 --> 01:17:58.132
such as salmon...

01:17:58.134 --> 01:18:00.168
I'm fine, okay?

01:18:00.170 --> 01:18:01.502
Okay.

01:18:01.504 --> 01:18:03.137
Sturgeon and stripers...

01:18:03.139 --> 01:18:04.672
[ Knock on door ] And every
style of fishing.

01:18:04.674 --> 01:18:07.675
With blue skies, gorgeous
green mountainsides

01:18:07.677 --> 01:18:09.610
and crystal-clear... man:
Sign here.

01:18:09.612 --> 01:18:12.346
Julie: Thanks.

01:18:12.348 --> 01:18:13.948
It's from mom and dad.

01:18:15.017 --> 01:18:16.684
If it's another monet poster

01:18:16.686 --> 01:18:17.852
to cheer us up,

01:18:17.854 --> 01:18:19.487
I swear I'll have an aneurysm.

01:18:19.489 --> 01:18:21.189
Mom's not coming this weekend.

01:18:21.191 --> 01:18:24.425
She says she and dad
are too busy

01:18:24.427 --> 01:18:27.361
and we should go down for
the long weekend.

01:18:27.363 --> 01:18:29.330
Hmm. Guess she doesn't need us

01:18:29.332 --> 01:18:30.832
to babysit her anymore.

01:18:30.834 --> 01:18:32.066
That's good, right?

01:18:32.068 --> 01:18:33.935
Yeah.

01:18:35.637 --> 01:18:37.105
Whoa.

01:18:37.107 --> 01:18:38.539
You should see this.

01:18:43.145 --> 01:18:45.246
Heh. What happened?

01:18:45.248 --> 01:18:46.747
Folie à deux.

01:18:46.749 --> 01:18:48.116
What?

01:18:48.118 --> 01:18:51.953
Basically, they've gone crazy.

01:18:51.955 --> 01:18:54.689
So, should we?

01:18:54.691 --> 01:18:56.023
What?

01:18:56.025 --> 01:18:58.459
Go down for the long weekend?

01:19:03.298 --> 01:19:05.633
[ Overlapping chatter ]

01:19:08.770 --> 01:19:11.005
God, can you handle this?

01:19:11.007 --> 01:19:12.607
Can you?

01:19:33.929 --> 01:19:36.864
And for a $100 contribution,

01:19:36.866 --> 01:19:40.034
we teach people to make these.

01:19:40.036 --> 01:19:42.570
And what is so lovely,

01:19:42.572 --> 01:19:44.572
your father said to me,

01:19:44.574 --> 01:19:48.943
"Mrs. Winereib, we could
use these dolls

01:19:48.945 --> 01:19:50.878
to decorate the hospital."

01:19:50.880 --> 01:19:52.346
He did?

01:19:52.348 --> 01:19:53.981
It's great.

01:19:53.983 --> 01:19:55.283
It's just we're used to dad

01:19:55.285 --> 01:19:57.685
being kind of a control
freak about design.

01:19:57.687 --> 01:19:59.554
Oh, I see.

01:19:59.556 --> 01:20:01.989
I hope you don't mind my asking,

01:20:01.991 --> 01:20:05.560
but my club was wondering about
Maria's favorite doll.

01:20:05.562 --> 01:20:06.394
Um...

01:20:06.396 --> 01:20:08.596
she hated dolls.

01:20:13.535 --> 01:20:15.536
We've raised nearly 30 million.

01:20:15.538 --> 01:20:18.105
And didn't they say we
couldn't do 10?

01:20:18.107 --> 01:20:19.540
Now if the miserable bastards

01:20:19.542 --> 01:20:22.443
on the New York state hospital
review panel say yes

01:20:22.445 --> 01:20:25.112
and your pal Nick in the
legislature lines up the votes,

01:20:25.114 --> 01:20:26.414
we got a shot.

01:20:26.416 --> 01:20:28.082
No, it's more than just a shot,
though.

01:20:28.084 --> 01:20:30.251
It's... I've built
hospitals before,

01:20:30.253 --> 01:20:32.353
but this is... I mean, we
are gonna have...

01:20:32.355 --> 01:20:34.555
if they let us do it,
we're gonna have

01:20:34.557 --> 01:20:35.923
arts-and-crafts rooms
on every floor,

01:20:35.925 --> 01:20:37.491
foldout beds in every room

01:20:37.493 --> 01:20:39.427
so parents, they can sleep
with their kids.

01:20:39.429 --> 01:20:42.430
You know, and I got the MTA to
give us a locomotive

01:20:42.432 --> 01:20:44.432
so the kids have a
place to play.

01:20:44.434 --> 01:20:46.267
And... but no. No, wait. It's...

01:20:46.269 --> 01:20:47.735
it's not about a building.

01:20:47.737 --> 01:20:49.604
This is about... this is about...

01:20:49.606 --> 01:20:51.739
it's about... it's
about a feeling.

01:20:53.208 --> 01:20:54.442
Yeah.

01:20:55.444 --> 01:20:58.512
Yeah, it's about
building a feeling.

01:20:58.514 --> 01:21:00.948
You know, Bruce used to be one
hell of a businessman

01:21:00.950 --> 01:21:02.150
before he met Brenda and John.

01:21:02.151 --> 01:21:03.618
[ Laughter ]

01:21:04.820 --> 01:21:06.621
Mrs. Fareri.

01:21:06.623 --> 01:21:07.455
Amy?

01:21:07.457 --> 01:21:09.156
Oh, look who's here, John.

01:21:09.158 --> 01:21:10.758
Hi. How are you?

01:21:10.760 --> 01:21:12.393
Yeah, I'm fine,

01:21:12.395 --> 01:21:13.995
but I'm really stressed

01:21:13.997 --> 01:21:15.830
about my final exams next week.

01:21:15.832 --> 01:21:17.398
Of course. Oh, it's
great to see you.

01:21:17.400 --> 01:21:18.699
You, too.

01:21:18.701 --> 01:21:20.201
Let me introduce you to
some of our friends.

01:21:20.203 --> 01:21:21.435
This is Bruce. Hi.

01:21:21.437 --> 01:21:22.770
This is a good
friend of Maria's.

01:21:30.245 --> 01:21:32.880
Oh. Lydia.

01:21:32.882 --> 01:21:34.248
John.

01:21:34.250 --> 01:21:35.516
I'm glad you came.

01:21:35.518 --> 01:21:37.218
I always support things

01:21:37.220 --> 01:21:39.687
that are good for our community.

01:21:39.689 --> 01:21:42.657
I just didn't expect it would
come from your direction.

01:21:42.659 --> 01:21:44.125
Oh. Ow.

01:21:44.127 --> 01:21:47.295
Well, you know, my daughter
would have felt the
same way as you.

01:21:47.297 --> 01:21:49.664
She was as tough on
me as you are.

01:21:50.932 --> 01:21:53.167
Wish I'd known her.

01:21:53.169 --> 01:21:55.069
Yeah, but the two of
you together,

01:21:55.071 --> 01:21:56.137
no, that would have...

01:21:56.139 --> 01:21:57.872
that would have finished me off.

01:22:29.404 --> 01:22:31.539
John: Here we go.

01:22:31.541 --> 01:22:33.841
This is good. Just right there.

01:22:33.843 --> 01:22:37.311
If anyone finds a cellphone, it
belongs to Mrs. Bennett.

01:22:37.313 --> 01:22:39.613
You can just toss those.

01:22:39.615 --> 01:22:41.515
But that's such a total waste.

01:22:41.517 --> 01:22:43.818
Well, thank you for pointing
that out, Steph.

01:22:43.820 --> 01:22:47.822
I have a whole fridge full that
wasn't even put out.

01:22:47.824 --> 01:22:48.824
Okay.

01:22:50.992 --> 01:22:52.593
What?

01:22:55.931 --> 01:22:57.531
Come here.

01:23:05.140 --> 01:23:07.074
[ Crying ]

01:23:12.347 --> 01:23:13.347
John: Honey.

01:23:13.349 --> 01:23:15.082
Come on. Let's go.

01:23:42.577 --> 01:23:45.179
[ Telephone rings ]

01:23:47.916 --> 01:23:51.118
[ Ring ]

01:23:53.789 --> 01:23:54.822
[ Ring ]

01:23:54.824 --> 01:23:55.756
Yeah?

01:23:55.758 --> 01:23:57.224
Eddie: I'm so sorry.

01:23:57.226 --> 01:23:58.226
It didn't pass.

01:23:58.227 --> 01:23:59.427
I know you did everything...

01:23:59.429 --> 01:24:01.162
Jesus! What?

01:24:01.164 --> 01:24:02.296
It was Eddie.

01:24:02.298 --> 01:24:04.198
The deal fell apart
in legislature.

01:24:04.200 --> 01:24:07.768
Wait. I thought... I thought
he had the votes.

01:24:12.274 --> 01:24:14.074
Hey, where are you going?

01:24:40.235 --> 01:24:41.669
What the hell, Nick? John.

01:24:41.671 --> 01:24:43.070
No, I don't want excuses.

01:24:43.072 --> 01:24:44.772
What kind of an idiot
votes against this?

01:24:44.774 --> 01:24:46.740
I want to talk to them. You
don't need to do that.

01:24:46.742 --> 01:24:47.975
Just tell me their names!

01:24:47.977 --> 01:24:50.044
You don't need to do that.
I want names!

01:24:50.046 --> 01:24:52.012
John, listen to me. We
didn't give up.

01:24:52.014 --> 01:24:54.849
We pushed it through.
It's done, okay?

01:24:54.851 --> 01:24:57.318
I was just about to call you.

01:24:58.653 --> 01:25:00.254
[ Chuckles ]

01:25:03.058 --> 01:25:04.525
Sorry.

01:25:04.527 --> 01:25:06.327
Congratulations.

01:25:06.329 --> 01:25:08.062
You did it.

01:25:08.064 --> 01:25:10.231
I honestly didn't think you could,

01:25:10.233 --> 01:25:12.132
but you did it.

01:25:13.368 --> 01:25:16.070
No. Maria did it.

01:25:23.845 --> 01:25:27.381
I just want to change before
we go to the office.

01:25:27.383 --> 01:25:31.018
Or we could take the day off,

01:25:31.020 --> 01:25:33.020
go back to bed.

01:25:48.870 --> 01:25:52.873
Maria: Sometimes it seems
like all is lost,

01:25:52.875 --> 01:25:55.743
and then along comes
a sunny day.

01:25:57.479 --> 01:26:00.381
Yeah, my name is on a building,

01:26:00.383 --> 01:26:04.585
but I left something else
behind that means
even more to me,

01:26:04.587 --> 01:26:07.788
a family that talks
to each other,

01:26:07.790 --> 01:26:10.658
that loves each other.

01:26:10.660 --> 01:26:13.294
They may have lost their glue,

01:26:13.296 --> 01:26:15.729
but they didn't come apart.

01:26:17.365 --> 01:26:19.833
Told you it wasn't a sad story.

